### Link Component

The `Link` component from `next/link` enables client-side navigation between pages:

```jsx
import Link from 'next/link';

export default function Nav() {
  return (
    <Link href="/about">
      About Us
    </Link>
  );
}
```

### Prefetching

By default, `Link` prefetches pages in the background when they appear in the viewport. This makes navigation instant. Disable it with `prefetch={false}`.

### Client-Side Transitions

Navigation via `Link` does not trigger a full page reload. Next.js fetches the new page's JavaScript and renders it client-side, providing app-like speed.

### useRouter Hook

The `useRouter` hook from `next/router` provides programmatic navigation:

```jsx
import { useRouter } from 'next/router';

export default function LoginButton() {
  const router = useRouter();

  const handleLogin = () => {
    // after login logic
    router.push('/dashboard');
  };

  return <button onClick={handleLogin}>Login</button>;
}
```

Other `useRouter` methods:
- `router.push(url)` — navigate to a URL
- `router.replace(url)` — navigate without adding to history
- `router.back()` — go back
- `router.reload()` — reload the current page
- `router.query` — access query parameters

### Shallow Routing

Change the URL without running data fetching methods:

```jsx
router.push('/?page=2', undefined, { shallow: true });
```

### Scroll to Top Behavior

By default, Next.js scrolls to the top of the page on navigation. Disable it:

```jsx
<Link href="/about" scroll={false}>About</Link>
```

codeExample:
import Link from 'next/link';
import { useRouter } from 'next/router';

export default function Navbar() {
  const router = useRouter();

  return (
    <nav>
      <Link href="/" className={router.pathname === '/' ? 'active' : ''}>
        Home
      </Link>
      <Link href="/blog">Blog</Link>
      <button onClick={() => router.push('/contact')}>Contact</button>
    </nav>
  );
}
